From: nix-wasm <eric@codebutler.com>
Subject: [PATCH] wasm: per-`mm` base-0 user-AS allocator + gate (T2.2, dark)

Phase 1 (Task 2.2): add the kernel-side half of per-process memory isolation —
a per-`mm` base-0 bump/free-list allocator for user mappings plus the
user-vs-kernel gate — and wire the runtime memory-lifecycle ABI
(wasm_user_mem_create at exec, wasm_user_mem_free at exit_mmap).

Landed DARK, behind an early-param feature flag (`wasm_user_as`, default OFF):

  * Flag OFF (default): mm->context.user_as_live is never set, so every gate
    site (do_mmap_private, the anon-zero clear, free_page_series, exit_mmap)
    takes the LEGACY shared alloc_pages_exact path. wasm_user_mem_create/free
    never fire. Boot is bit-for-bit the pre-0016 behavior — default boot stays
    green. The allocator and lifecycle wiring are compiled but inert.

  * Flag ON (`wasm_user_as=1`): exec calls wasm_user_mem_create + sets
    user_as_live; do_mmap_private routes through the per-mm allocator (returning
    a SMALL private offset in [USER_AS_BASE=0x10000, user_as_size)); the
    anon-zero clear routes through wasm_user_memzero; free_page_series frees back
    to the per-mm free-list (coalescing); exit_mmap drains it and calls
    wasm_user_mem_free. This is the path T2.3 will make default once user
    instantiation is flipped to the private memory; until then a flag-on
    USERSPACE can't actually run (the user module is still instantiated against
    the SHARED memory, so small private offsets have no backing) — which is
    EXACTLY why it is flagged off.

The DARK decision / why a flag (not "compute private offsets, return shared
addresses"): the T2.1 runtime resolver is `userMems.get(pid)?.memory ?? shared`,
so the instant wasm_user_mem_create registers a per-pid memory, ALL of that
pid's uaccess (copy_to_user / memzero / strncpy) resolves to the (empty) private
memory while the process still runs against shared memory — boot breaks. The
only way to keep default boot green AND exercise create/free + the allocator is
to gate the whole user-AS path off by default and prove it via a flag-on
in-kernel self-test, deferring the running-process proof to T2.3. This is design
escape-hatch (a) (docs/.../2026-06-19-task2-perprocess-memory-design.md §5;
.superpowers/sdd/task-2.2-report.md). The self-test (late_initcall, flag-on
only) runs the bump/free-list math on a throwaway mm_context (no runtime memory)
and prints "WASM_USER_AS_SELFTEST: PASS first=0x..." with the first offset it
hands out (>= 0x10000), proving the allocator + lifecycle wiring.

Page accounting: the runtime grows the private memory in WASM pages
(WASM_PAGE_SIZE = 64 KiB), independent of the kernel PAGE_SIZE. Offsets are
PAGE_SIZE-aligned; the private memory SIZE and the grow delta are tracked in
WASM pages.

File-backed mmap audit (design §1 / risks §9): the sole file-backed user
vm_mmap is the CODE image (binfmt_wasm.c), mapped BEFORE user_as_live is set, so
it stays SHARED and never reaches the private allocator. musl mallocng allocates
anonymously. No file-backed mapping reaches the private allocator in scope; the
private-AS branch WARNs-and-fails on a file-backed vma rather than letting
kernel_read write into a private offset, documenting the invariant. The
bounce-buffer path is therefore unreachable and intentionally NOT implemented
(it would be dead code).

Bumps WASM_HOSTBRIDGE_ABI to 2 (matching the runtime) and declares
wasm_user_mem_create/grow/free in asm/wasm.h beside the 0014/0015 bridge decls.

Free path gates on the OWNING mm, not current->mm: during process exit,
exit_mm() sets current->mm = NULL BEFORE mmput()->exit_mmap() runs the per-VMA
teardown (delete_vma -> put_nommu_region -> free_page_series), so a current->mm
gate would be false there and still-mapped PRIVATE regions (small offsets) would
fall through to virt_to_page()/put_page() on a bogus struct page. The owning mm
is threaded down free_page_series(mm, ...) / __put_nommu_region(mm, ...) /
put_nommu_region(mm, ...), supplied from delete_vma()'s mm arg (exit_mmap and
do_munmap both have it) and from vma->vm_mm on the do_mmap_private error_free and
vmi_shrink_vma paths. BOTH free entry points (exit_mmap, do_munmap) now gate on
the owning mm. The self-test covers the free path heavily (coalesce of adjacent
extents, the brk-retract `again` reclaim, overflow->grow fail-closed) since the
review found a Critical there.

diff --git a/arch/wasm/include/asm/mmu.h b/arch/wasm/include/asm/mmu.h
new file mode 100644
index 000000000..09d25ae08
--- /dev/null
+++ b/arch/wasm/include/asm/mmu.h
@@ -0,0 +1,45 @@
+/* SPDX-License-Identifier: GPL-2.0 */
+/*
+ * wasm mm_context_t — the NOMMU base (asm-generic/mmu.h) plus the per-process
+ * base-0 user-address-space allocator state (Task 2).
+ *
+ * The generic NOMMU mm_context_t carries only `end_brk`. The wasm per-process
+ * memory split (Task 2) gives each process a distinct base-0 WebAssembly.Memory
+ * and runs a per-`mm` bump/free-list allocator over it; these fields hold that
+ * allocator's state. `user_as_live` is the user-vs-kernel discriminator (set at
+ * exec, only when the `wasm_user_as` early-param is on); when clear, every
+ * allocation path falls back to the legacy shared NOMMU pool, so the default
+ * build is unchanged (landed dark).
+ */
+#ifndef _ASM_WASM_MMU_H
+#define _ASM_WASM_MMU_H
+
+#ifndef __ASSEMBLY__
+
+#include <linux/types.h>
+#include <linux/list.h>
+
+typedef struct {
+	unsigned long		end_brk;	/* generic NOMMU brk clamp */
+
+#ifdef CONFIG_BINFMT_ELF_FDPIC
+	unsigned long		exec_fdpic_loadmap;
+	unsigned long		interp_fdpic_loadmap;
+#endif
+
+	/* Task 2: per-process base-0 user address space (see banner). */
+	unsigned long		user_as_size;	/* private memory size, bytes */
+	unsigned long		user_as_brk;	/* next free bump offset */
+	struct list_head	user_as_free;	/* freed [start,len) extents */
+	bool			user_as_live;	/* set at exec; user/kernel gate */
+} mm_context_t;
+
+#endif /* __ASSEMBLY__ */
+
+/*
+ * Layout within [0, user_as_size): guard page at 0 (NULL traps), then user
+ * mappings from USER_AS_BASE upward. 0x10000 == one wasm page (64 KiB).
+ */
+#define USER_AS_BASE		0x10000UL
+
+#endif /* _ASM_WASM_MMU_H */
diff --git a/arch/wasm/include/asm/user_as.h b/arch/wasm/include/asm/user_as.h
new file mode 100644
index 000000000..7d8b2189b
--- /dev/null
+++ b/arch/wasm/include/asm/user_as.h
@@ -0,0 +1,54 @@
+/* SPDX-License-Identifier: GPL-2.0 */
+/*
+ * Per-`mm` base-0 user-address-space allocator (Task 2) — the kernel half of
+ * per-process memory isolation on the wasm NOMMU port. See arch/wasm/mm/user_as.c.
+ *
+ * Gate: wasm_user_as_active(mm) == (wasm_user_as_enabled && mm && user_as_live).
+ * When false the caller takes the legacy shared NOMMU pool path, so with the
+ * flag off (default) the whole subsystem is inert (landed dark).
+ */
+#ifndef _ASM_WASM_USER_AS_H
+#define _ASM_WASM_USER_AS_H
+
+#include <linux/types.h>
+#include <linux/mm_types.h>
+#include <asm/mmu.h>
+
+/* Runtime feature flag (early_param "wasm_user_as"); default false → dark. */
+extern bool wasm_user_as_enabled;
+
+static inline bool wasm_user_as_active(struct mm_struct *mm)
+{
+	return wasm_user_as_enabled && mm && mm->context.user_as_live;
+}
+
+/*
+ * Initialise the per-`mm` allocator for `mm` with a private space of
+ * `size_bytes` (rounded to wasm pages). Sets user_as_live. Called from exec
+ * after wasm_user_mem_create succeeds. Returns 0 on success.
+ */
+int wasm_user_as_init(struct mm_struct *mm, unsigned long size_bytes);
+
+/*
+ * Allocate `len` bytes (page-rounded) from `mm`'s private space: first-fit the
+ * free-list, else bump from user_as_brk (growing the private memory via
+ * wasm_user_mem_grow on overflow). Returns the base offset (>= USER_AS_BASE), or
+ * 0 on failure.
+ */
+unsigned long wasm_user_as_alloc(struct mm_struct *mm, unsigned long len);
+
+/* Free [base, base+len) back to `mm`'s free-list (coalescing). */
+void wasm_user_as_free_extent(struct mm_struct *mm, unsigned long base,
+			      unsigned long len);
+
+/*
+ * Tear down `mm`'s allocator: drain the free-list and call wasm_user_mem_free.
+ * Called from exit_mmap. Safe when never initialised.
+ */
+void wasm_user_as_destroy(struct mm_struct *mm);
+
+/* Zero `n` bytes at private user offset `uaddr` in `mm`'s space (anon/BSS clear). */
+void wasm_user_as_memzero(struct mm_struct *mm, unsigned long uaddr,
+			  unsigned long n);
+
+#endif /* _ASM_WASM_USER_AS_H */
diff --git a/arch/wasm/include/asm/wasm.h b/arch/wasm/include/asm/wasm.h
index 690fdb5bc..076dbfcef 100644
--- a/arch/wasm/include/asm/wasm.h
+++ b/arch/wasm/include/asm/wasm.h
@@ -3,6 +3,15 @@
 #ifndef _ASM_WASM_WASM_H
 #define _ASM_WASM_WASM_H
 
+/*
+ * Cross-repo host-bridge ABI version. Must match the runtime
+ * (runtime/hostbridge.js WASM_HOSTBRIDGE_ABI). v1 = the uaccess copy ops
+ * (0014/0015). v2 (Task 2) adds the per-process memory-lifecycle ops
+ * (wasm_user_mem_create/grow/free) declared below. Bumped to 2 to match the
+ * runtime that already ships the v2 ops.
+ */
+#define WASM_HOSTBRIDGE_ABI 2
+
 /* These are symbols imported from the Wasm host. */
 
 extern void wasm_panic(const char *msg);
@@ -31,6 +40,22 @@ extern long wasm_user_strncpy(int pid, unsigned long dst_kaddr,
 extern unsigned long wasm_user_memzero(int pid, unsigned long uaddr,
 				       unsigned long n);
 
+/*
+ * Task 2 (ABI v2) memory-lifecycle imports. Mint / grow / drop a process's
+ * private base-0 WebAssembly.Memory, keyed by pid. The runtime owns the memory;
+ * the kernel's per-`mm` allocator (arch/wasm/mm/user_as.c) hands out offsets.
+ *   create: mint the per-pid {memory,table}; re-exec replaces the prior one.
+ *           Returns 0 on success, <0 on failure.
+ *   grow:   memory.grow(delta_pages) on the per-pid memory (NOT index 0, the
+ *           shared kernel memory). Returns the new page count, or -1 on failure.
+ *   free:   drop the registry entry at exit_mmap teardown.
+ * Declared here (beside the 0014/0015 bridge decls) per the T2.1 review so any
+ * wasm kernel code can reach the lifecycle ABI.
+ */
+extern long          wasm_user_mem_create(int pid, unsigned long init_pages);
+extern unsigned long wasm_user_mem_grow(int pid, unsigned long delta_pages);
+extern void          wasm_user_mem_free(int pid);
+
 extern void wasm_start_cpu(unsigned int cpu, struct task_struct *idle_task);
 extern void wasm_stop_cpu(unsigned int cpu);
 
